# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: esbuild
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:esbuild/esbuild] esbuild is used in Vite, a front-end build-tool and development server, and the Phoenix Framework.
[src:esbuild/esbuild] It is included as a bundler for Angular since v17, Ruby on Rails since v7, and for Netlify Functions.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This guide gives you all you need to get started with JavaScript module syntax.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] JavaScript programs started off pretty small — most of its usage in the early days was to do isolated scripting tasks, providing a bit of interactivity to your web pages where needed, so large scripts were generally not needed.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Fast forward a few years and we now have complete applications being run in browsers with a lot of JavaScript, as well as JavaScript being used in other contexts (Node.js, for example).
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Complex projects necessitate a mechanism for splitting JavaScript programs into separate modules that can be imported when needed.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Node.js has had this ability for a long time, and there are a number of JavaScript libraries and frameworks that enable module usage (for example, other CommonJS and AMD-based module systems like RequireJS, webpack, and Babel).
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] All modern browsers support module features natively without needing transpilation.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] It can only be a good thing — browsers can optimize loading of modules, making it more efficient than having to use a library and do all of that extra client-side processing and extra round trips.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] It does not obsolete bundlers like webpack, though — bundlers still do a good job at partitioning code into reasonably sized chunks, and are able to do other optimizations like minification, dead code elimination, and tree-shaking.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] To demonstrate usage of modules, we've created a set of examples that you can find on GitHub.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] These examples demonstrate a set of modules that create a `<canvas>` element on a webpage, and then draw (and report information about) different shapes on the canvas.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] These are fairly trivial, but have been kept deliberately simple to demonstrate modules clearly.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Throughout this article, we've used `.js` extensions for our module files, but in other resources you may see the `.mjs` extension used instead.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] V8's documentation recommends this, for example.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] However, we decided to keep using `.js`, at least for the moment.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] To get modules to work correctly in a browser, you need to make sure that your server is serving them with a `Content-Type` header that contains a JavaScript MIME type such as `text/javascript`.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] If you don't, you'll get a strict MIME type checking error along the lines of "The server responded with a non-JavaScript MIME type" and the browser won't run your JavaScript.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Most servers already set the correct type for `.js` files, but not yet for `.mjs` files.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Servers that already serve `.mjs` files correctly include GitHub Pages and `http-server` for Node.js.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This is OK if you are using such an environment already, or if you aren't but you know what you are doing and have access (i.e., you can configure your server to set the correct `Content-Type` for `.mjs` files).
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] It could however cause confusion if you don't control the server you are serving files from, or are publishing files for public use, as we are here.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] For learning and portability purposes, we decided to keep to `.js`.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] If you really value the clarity of using `.mjs` for modules versus using `.js` for "normal" JavaScript files, but don't want to run into the problem described above, you could always use `.mjs` during development and convert them to `.js` during your build step.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The first thing you do to get access to module features is export them.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This is done using the `export` statement.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] You can export functions, `var`, `let`, `const`, and — as we'll see later — classes.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] They need to be top-level items: for example, you can't use `export` inside a function.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] A more convenient way of exporting all the items you want to export is to use a single export statement at the end of your module file, followed by a comma-separated list of the features you want to export wrapped in curly braces.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Once you've exported some features out of your module, you need to import them into your script to be able to use them.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] You use the `import` statement, followed by a comma-separated list of the features you want to import wrapped in curly braces, followed by the keyword `from`, followed by the *module specifier*.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The *module specifier* provides a string that the JavaScript environment can resolve to a path to the module file.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] In a browser, this could be a path relative to the site root, which for our `basic-modules` example would be `/js-examples/module-examples/basic-modules`.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] However, here we are instead using the dot (`.`) syntax to mean "the current location", followed by the relative path to the file we are trying to find.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This is much better than writing out the entire absolute path each time, as relative paths are shorter and make the URL portable — the example will still work if you move it to a different location in the site hierarchy.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] You can see such lines in action in `main.js`.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Once you've imported the features into your script, you can use them just like they were defined inside the same file.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Import maps allow developers to instead specify almost any text they want in the module specifier when importing a module; the map provides a corresponding value that will replace the text when the module URL is resolved.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] For example, the `imports` key in the import map below defines a "module specifier map" JSON object where the property names can be used as module specifiers, and the corresponding values will be substituted when the browser resolves the module URL.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The values must be absolute or relative URLs.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Relative URLs are resolved to absolute URL addresses using the base URL of the document containing the import map.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The import map is defined using a JSON object inside a `<script>` element with the `type` attribute set to `importmap`.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Note that an import map only applies to the document — the specification does not cover how to apply an import map in a worker or worklet context.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] With this map you can now use the property names above as module specifiers.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] If there is no trailing forward slash on the module specifier key then the whole module specifier key is matched and substituted.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] For example, below we match bare module names, and remap a URL to another path.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] If the module specifier has a trailing forward slash then the value must have one as well, and the key is matched as a "path prefix".
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This allows remapping of whole classes of URLs.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] It is possible for multiple keys in an import map to be valid matches for a module specifier.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] For example, a module specifier of `shapes/circle/` could match the module specifier keys `shapes/` and `shapes/circle/`.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] In this case the browser will select the most specific (longest) matching module specifier key.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Import maps allow modules to be imported using bare module names (as in Node.js), and can also simulate importing modules from packages, both with and without file extensions.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] While not shown above, they also allow particular versions of a library to be imported, based on the path of the script that is importing the module.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Generally they let developers write more ergonomic import code, and make it easier to manage the different versions and dependencies of modules used by a site.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This can reduce the effort required to use the same JavaScript libraries in both browser and server.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The following sections expand on the various features outlined above.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] In some JavaScript environments, such as Node.js, you can use bare names for the module specifier.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This works because the environment can resolve module names to a standard location in the file system.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] For example, you might use the following syntax to import the "square" module.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] To use bare names on a browser you need an import map, which provides the information needed by the browser to resolve module specifiers to URLs (JavaScript will throw a `TypeError` if it attempts to import a module specifier that can't be resolved to a module location).
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Below you can see a map that defines a `square` module specifier key, which in this case maps to a relative address value.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Module specifier map entries, where both the specifier key and its associated value have a trailing forward slash (`/`), can be used as a path-prefix.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This allows the remapping of a whole set of import URLs from one location to another.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] It can also be used to emulate working with "packages and modules", such as you might see in the Node ecosystem.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] It is possible to import `fp` above without the `.js` file extension, but you would need to create a bare module specifier key for that file, such as `lodash/fp`, rather than using the path.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This may be reasonable for just one module, but scales poorly if you wish to import many modules.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] A module specifier key doesn't have to be path — it can also be an absolute URL (or a URL-like relative path like `./`, `../`, `/`).
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This may be useful if you want to remap a module that has absolute paths to a resource with your own local resources.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Ecosystems like Node use package managers such as npm to manage modules and their dependencies.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The package manager ensures that each module is separated from other modules and their dependencies.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] As a result, while a complex application might include the same module multiple times with several different versions in different parts of the module graph, users do not need to think about this complexity.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Import maps similarly allow you to have multiple versions of dependencies in your application and refer to them using the same module specifier.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] You implement this with the `scopes` key, which allows you to provide module specifier maps that will be used depending on the path of the script performing the import.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] With this mapping, if a script with a URL that contains `/node_modules/dependency/` imports `cool-module`, the version in `/node_modules/some/other/location/cool-module/index.js` will be used.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The map in `imports` is used as a fallback if there is no matching scope in the scoped map, or the matching scopes don't contain a matching specifier.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] For example, if `cool-module` is imported from a script with a non-matching scope path, then the module specifier map in `imports` will be used instead, mapping to the version in `/node_modules/cool-module/index.js`.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Note that the path used to select a scope does not affect how the address is resolved.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The value in the mapped path does not have to match the scopes path, and relative paths are still resolved to the base URL of the script that contains the import map.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Just as for module specifier maps, you can have many scope keys, and these may contain overlapping paths.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] If multiple scopes match the referrer URL, then the most specific scope path is checked first (the longest scope key) for a matching specifier.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The browsers will fall back to the next most specific matching scoped path if there is no matching specifier, and so on.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] If there is no matching specifier in any of the matching scopes, the browser checks for a match in the module specifier map in the `imports` key.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Script files used by websites often have hashed filenames to simplify caching.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The downside of this approach is that if a module changes, any modules that import it using its hashed filename will also need to be updated/regenerated.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This potentially results in a cascade of updates, which is wasteful of network resources.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Import maps provide a convenient solution to this problem.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Rather than depending on specific hashed filenames, applications and scripts instead depend on an un-hashed version of the module name (address).
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] An import map like the one below then provides a mapping to the actual script file.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] If `dependency_script` changes, then its hash contained in the file name changes as well.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] In this case, we only need to update the import map to reflect the changed name of the module.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] We don't have to update the source of any JavaScript code that depends on it, because the specifier in the import statement does not change.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] One exciting feature that a unified module architecture brings is the ability to load non-JavaScript resources as modules.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] For example, you can import JSON as a JavaScript object, or import CSS as a `CSSStyleSheet` object.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] You must explicitly declare what kind of resource you are importing.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] By default, the browser assumes that the resource is JavaScript, and will throw an error if the resolved resource is something else.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Browsers will also perform validation on the module type, and fail if, for example, `./data.json` does not resolve to a JSON file.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This ensures that you don't accidentally execute code when you just intend to import data.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Once imported successfully, you can now use the imported value as a normal JavaScript object or `CSSStyleSheet` object.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Now we just need to apply the `main.js` module to our HTML page.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This is very similar to how we apply a regular script to a page, with a few notable differences.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] First of all, you need to include `type="module"` in the `<script>` element, to declare this script as a module.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] You can only use `import` and `export` statements inside modules, not regular scripts.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] An error will be thrown if your `<script>` element doesn't have the `type="module"` attribute and attempts to import other modules.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] You should generally define all your modules in separate files.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Modules declared inline in HTML can only import other modules, but anything they export will not be accessible by other modules (because they don't have a URL).
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Module-defined variables are scoped to the module unless explicitly attached to the global object.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] On the other hand, globally-defined variables are available within the module.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The page would still render `Hello`, because the global variables `text` and `document` are available in the module.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The functionality we've exported so far has been comprised of **named exports** — each item (be it a function, `const`, etc.) has been referred to by its name upon export, and that name has been used to refer to it on import as well.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Let's look at an example as we explain how it works.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] In our basic-modules `square.js` you can find a function called `randomSquare()` that creates a square with a random color, size, and position.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This is because there is only one default export allowed per module, and we know that `randomSquare` is it.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] So far, our canvas shape drawing modules seem to be working OK.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] But what happens if we try to add a module that deals with drawing another shape, like a circle or triangle?
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] These shapes would probably have associated functions like `draw()`, `reportArea()`, etc. too; if we tried to import different functions of the same name into the same top-level module file, we'd end up with conflicts and errors.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Fortunately there are a number of ways to get around this.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] We'll look at these in the following sections.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Inside your `import` and `export` statement's curly braces, you can use the keyword `as` along with a new feature name, to change the identifying name you will use for a feature inside the top-level module.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] In our renaming directory you'll see the same module system as in the previous example, except that we've added `circle.js` and `triangle.js` modules to draw and report on circles and triangles.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The browser would throw an error such as "SyntaxError: redeclaration of import name" (Firefox).
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Note that you could solve the problem in the module files instead, e.g.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] What style you use is up to you, however it arguably makes more sense to leave your module code alone, and make the changes in the imports.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This especially makes sense when you are importing from third party modules that you don't have any control over.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The above method works OK, but it's a little messy and long-winded.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] An even better solution is to import each module's features inside a module object.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This grabs all the exports available inside `module.js`, and makes them available as members of an object `Module`, effectively giving it its own namespace.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] If you go to our module-objects directory, you'll see the same example again, but rewritten to take advantage of this new syntax.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] So you can now write the code just the same as before (as long as you include the object names where needed), and the imports are much neater.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] As we hinted at earlier, you can also export and import classes; this is another option for avoiding conflicts in your code, and is especially useful if you've already got your module code written in an object-oriented style.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] You can see an example of our shape drawing module rewritten with ES classes in our classes directory.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] There will be times where you'll want to aggregate modules together.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] You might have multiple levels of dependencies, where you want to simplify things, combining several submodules into one parent module.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] For an example, see our module-aggregation directory.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] In this example (based on our earlier classes example) we've got an extra module called `shapes.js`, which aggregates all the functionality from `circle.js`, `square.js`, and `triangle.js` together.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] We've also moved our submodules inside a subdirectory inside the `modules` directory called `shapes`.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] In each of the submodules, the export is of the same form, e.g.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] These grab the exports from the individual submodules and effectively make them available from the `shapes.js` module.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] A recent addition to JavaScript modules functionality is dynamic module loading.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This allows you to dynamically load modules only when they are needed, rather than having to load everything up front.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This has some obvious performance advantages; let's read on and see how it works.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This new functionality allows you to call `import()` as a function, passing it the path to the module as a parameter.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] It returns a `Promise`, which fulfills with a module object (see Creating a module object) giving you access to that object's exports.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] In the dynamic-module-imports directory we've got another example based on our classes example.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This time however we are not drawing anything on the canvas when the example loads.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Instead, we include three buttons — "Circle", "Square", and "Triangle" — that, when pressed, dynamically load the required module and then use it to draw the associated shape.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] In this example we've only made changes to our `index.html` and `main.js` files — the module exports remain the same as before.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Note that, because the promise fulfillment returns a module object, the class is then made a subfeature of the object, hence we now need to access the constructor with `Module.` prepended to it, e.g., `Module.Square( /* … */ )`.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Another advantage of dynamic imports is that they are always available, even in script environments.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Therefore, if you have an existing `<script>` tag in your HTML that doesn't have `type="module"`, you can still reuse code distributed as modules by dynamically importing it.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Top level await is a feature available within modules.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This means the `await` keyword can be used.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] It allows modules to act as big asynchronous functions meaning code can be evaluated before use in parent modules, but without blocking sibling modules from loading.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] You can find all the files and code described in this section within the `top-level-await` directory, which extends from the previous examples.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Then we'll create a module called `getColors.js` which uses a fetch request to load the `colors.json` file and return the data as an object.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] We're using the keyword `await` before specifying the constant `colors` to export.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This means any other modules which include this one will wait until `colors` has been downloaded and parsed before using it.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This is useful because the code within `main.js` won't execute until the code in `getColors.js` has run.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] However it won't block other modules being loaded.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] For instance our `canvas.js` module will continue to load while `colors` is being fetched.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] In this case, it means that the imported values are available in the module's code even before the place that declares them, and that the imported module's side effects are produced before the rest of the module's code starts running.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Still, it is considered good practice to put all your imports at the top of the code, which makes it easier to analyze dependencies.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Modules can import other modules, and those modules can import other modules, and so on.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This forms a directed graph called the "dependency graph".
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] In an ideal world, this graph is acyclic.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] In this case, the graph can be evaluated using a depth-first traversal.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Cyclic import arises if module `a` imports module `b`, but `b` directly or indirectly depends on `a`.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The imported variable's value is only retrieved when the variable is actually used (hence allowing live bindings), and only if the variable remains uninitialized at that time will a `ReferenceError` be thrown.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] In this example, both `a` and `b` are used asynchronously.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Therefore, at the time the module is evaluated, neither `b` nor `a` is actually read, so the rest of the code is executed as normal, and the two `export` declarations produce the values of `a` and `b`.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Then, after the timeout, both `a` and `b` are available, so the two `console.log` statements also execute as normal.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This is because when JavaScript evaluates `a.js`, it needs to first evaluate `b.js`, the dependency of `a.js`.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] However, `b.js` uses `a`, which is not yet available.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] This is because the evaluation of `b.js` completes normally, so the value of `b` is available when `a.js` is evaluated.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] You should usually avoid cyclic imports in your project, because they make your code more error-prone.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] However, cyclic imports can also occur if the libraries depend on each other, which is harder to fix.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] The introduction of modules encourages the JavaScript ecosystem to distribute and reuse code in a modular fashion.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] However, that doesn't necessarily mean a piece of JavaScript code can run in every environment.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Suppose you discovered a module that generates SHA hashes of your user's password.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Can you use it in the browser front end?
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Modules still have access to global variables, as demonstrated previously.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] If the module references globals like `window`, it can run in the browser, but will throw an error in your Node.js server, because `window` is not available there.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Similarly, if the code requires access to `process` to be functional, it can only be used in Node.js.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] In order to maximize the reusability of a module, it is often advised to make the code "isomorphic" — that is, exhibits the same behavior in every runtime.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] These practices are not unique to modules.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Still, with the trend of code reusability and modularization, you are encouraged to make your code cross-platform so that it can be enjoyed by as many people as possible.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Runtimes like Node.js are also actively implementing web APIs where possible to improve interoperability with the web.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Here are a few tips that may help you if you are having trouble getting your modules to work.
[src:esbuild/guide-modules] Feel free to add to the list if you discover more!
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] Minification can be distinguished from the more general concept of data compression in that the minified source can be interpreted immediately without the need for a decompression step: the same interpreter can work with both the original as well as with the minified source.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] The goals of minification are not the same as the goals of obfuscation; the former is often intended to be reversed using a pretty printer or unminifier.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] However, to achieve its goals, minification sometimes uses techniques also used by obfuscation; for example, shortening variable names and refactoring the source code.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] When minification uses such techniques, the pretty-printer or unminifier can only fully reverse the minification process if it is supplied details of the transformations done by such techniques.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] If not supplied those details, the reversed source code will contain different variable names and control flow, even though it will have the same functionality as the original source code.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] In 2001 Douglas Crockford introduced JSMin, which removed comments and whitespace from JavaScript code.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] It was followed by YUI Compressor in 2007.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] In 2009, Google opened up its Closure toolkit, including Closure Compiler which contained a source mapping feature together with a Firefox extension called Closure Inspector.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] In 2010, Mihai Bazon introduced UglifyJS, which was superseded by UglifyJS2 in 2012; the rewrite was to allow for source map support.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] From 2017, Alex Lam took over maintenance and development of UglifyJS2, replacing it with UglifyJS3 which unified the CLI with the API.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] In 2018, Terser has been forked from uglify-es and has gained momentum since; in 2020 it outstripped UglifyJS when measured in daily downloads.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] Since late 2018, Terser has recommended the bundler RollupJS.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] A **source map** is a file format that allows software tools for JavaScript to display different code to a user than the code actually executed by the computer.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] For example, to aid in debugging of minified code, by "mapping" this code to the original unminified source code instead.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] The original format was created by Joseph Schorr as part of the Closure Inspector minification project.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] Version 2 and 3 of the format reduced the size of the map files considerably.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] In 2024, source maps were standardized by Ecma International's TC39 technical committee as ECMA-426.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] JavaScript and Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) resources may be minified, preserving their behavior while considerably reducing their file size.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] Libraries available online are capable of minification and optimization to varying degrees.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] Some libraries also merge multiple script files into a single file for client download.
[src:esbuild/minification-programming] JavaScript source maps can make code readable and debuggable even after it has been combined and minified.
[src:esbuild/module-bundler] A **module bundler** is a software development tool that takes multiple source files and their dependencies (*modules*) and combines them into one or more output files called *bundles*.
[src:esbuild/module-bundler] Module bundlers are commonly used in front-end web development to package JavaScript, CSS and other assets for efficient delivery to web browsers.
[src:esbuild/module-bundler] Module bundlers typically start from one or more entry points and build a dependency graph of all imported modules before producing the final bundles, often applying optimisations such as minification and tree shaking.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] A source-to-source translator converts between programming languages that operate at approximately the same level of abstraction, while a traditional compiler translates from a higher level language to a lower level language.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] For example, a source-to-source translator may perform a translation of a program from Python to JavaScript, while a traditional compiler translates from a language like C to assembly or Java to bytecode.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] An automatic parallelizing compiler will frequently take in a high level language program as an input and then transform the code and annotate it with parallel code annotations (e.g., OpenMP) or language constructs (e.g.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Another purpose of source-to-source-compiling is translating legacy code to use the next version of the underlying programming language or an application programming interface (API) that breaks backward compatibility.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Transcompilers may either keep translated code structure as close to the source code as possible to ease development and debugging of the original source code or may change the structure of the original code so much that the translated code does not look like the source code.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Examples include Closure Compiler, CoffeeScript, Dart, Haxe, Opal, TypeScript and Emscripten.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] So called *Assembly language translators* are a class of source-to-source translators converting code from one assembly language into another, including (but not limited to) across different processor families and system platforms.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Intel marketed their 16-bit processor 8086 to be source compatible to the 8080, an 8-bit processor.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] To support this, Intel had an ISIS-II-based translator from 8080 to 8086 source code named CONV86 (also referred to as CONV-86 and CONVERT 86) available to OEM customers since 1978, possibly the earliest program of this kind.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] It supported multiple levels of translation and ran at 2 MHz on an Intel Microprocessor Development System MDS-800 with 8-inch floppy drives.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] According to user reports, it did not work very reliably.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Seattle Computer Products (SCP) offered TRANS86.COM, written by Tim Paterson in 1980 while developing 86-DOS.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Also, performing only a mere transliteration, the brute-force single-pass translator did not carry out any register and jump optimizations.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] The SCP version 1 of TRANS86.COM ran on Z80-based systems.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Once 86-DOS was running, Paterson, in a self-hosting-inspired approach, utilized TRANS86 to convert itself into a program running under 86-DOS.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Numbered version 2, this was named TRANS.COM instead.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Later in 1982, the translator was apparently also available from Microsoft.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Also named TRANS86, Sorcim offered an 8080 to 8086 translator as well since December 1980.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Like SCP's program it was designed to port CP/M-80 application code (in ASM, MAC, RMAC or ACT80 assembly format) to MS-DOS (in a format compatible with ACT86).
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] In ACT80 format it also supported a few Z80 mnemonics.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] The translation occurred on an instruction-by-instruction basis with some optimization applied to conditional jumps.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] The program ran under CP/M-80, MP/M-80 and Cromemco DOS with a minimum of 24 KB of RAM, and had no restrictions on the source file size.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Much more sophisticated and the first to introduce optimizing compiler technologies into the source translation process was Digital Research's XLT86 1.0 in September 1981.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] The program was written by Gary Kildall and translated .ASM source code for the Intel 8080 processor (in a format compatible with ASM, MAC or RMAC assemblers) into .A86 source code for the 8086 (compatible with ASM86).
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] XLT86.COM itself was written in PL/I-80 for CP/M-80 platforms.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] The program occupied 30 KB of RAM for itself plus additional memory for the program graph.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] On a 64 KB memory system, the maximum source file size supported was about 6 KB, so that larger files had to be broken down accordingly before translation.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Alternatively, XLT86 was also available for DEC VAX/VMS.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Although XLT86's input and output worked on source-code level, the translator's in-memory representation of the program and the applied code optimizing technologies set the foundation to binary recompilation.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] 2500 AD Software offered an 8080 to 8086 source-code translator as part of their XASM suite for CP/M-80 machines with Z80 as well as for Zilog ZEUS and Olivetti PCOS systems.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Since 1979, Zilog offered a Z80 to Z8000 translator as part of their PDS 8000 development system.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Advanced Micro Computers (AMC) and 2500 AD Software offered Z80 to Z8000 translators as well.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] The latter was named TRANS and was available for Z80 CP/M, CP/M-86, MS-DOS and PCOS.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] The Z88DK development kit provides a Z80 to i486 source code translator targeting nasm named "to86.awk", written in 2008 by Stefano Bodrato.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] It is in turn based on an 8080 to Z80 converter written in 2003 by Douglas Beattie, Jr., named "toz80.awk".
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] In 2021, Brian Callahan wrote an 8080 CP/M 2.2 to MS-DOS source code translator targeting nasm named 8088ify.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] The first implementations of some programming languages started as transcompilers, and the default implementation for some of those languages are still transcompilers.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] In addition to the table below, a CoffeeScript maintainer provides a list of languages that compile to JavaScript.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] When developers want to switch to a different language while retaining most of an existing codebase, it might be better to use a transcompiler compared to rewriting the whole software by hand.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Depending on the quality of the transcompiler, the code may or may not need manual intervention in order to work properly.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] This is different from "transcompiled languages" where the specifications demand that the output source code always works without modification.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] All transcompilers used to port a codebase will expect manual adjustment of the output source code if there is a need to achieve maximum code quality in terms of readability and platform convention.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] A transcompiler pipeline is what results from *recursive transcompiling*.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] By stringing together multiple layers of tech, with a transcompile step between each layer, technology can be repeatedly transformed, effectively creating a distributed language independent specification.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] XSLT is a general-purpose transform tool that can be used between many different technologies, to create such a derivative code pipeline.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] By repeating this process, one can turn A → B → C → D → E → F and then back into A(v2).
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] Some information will be preserved through this pipeline, from A → A(v2), and that information (at an abstract level) demonstrates what each of the components A–F agree on.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] In each of the different versions that the transcompiler pipeline produces, that information is preserved.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] It might take on many different shapes and sizes, but by the time it comes back to A (v2), having been transcompiled six times in the pipeline above, the information returns to its original state.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] This information which survives the transform through each format, from A–F–A(v2), is (by definition) derivative content or derivative code.
[src:esbuild/source-to-source-compiler] There are also debugging utilities that map the transcompiled source code back to the original code; for example, JavaScript source maps allow mapping of the JavaScript code executed by a web browser back to the original source in a transcompiled-to-JavaScript language.
[src:esbuild/tree-shaking] It relies on the import and export statements to detect if code modules are exported and imported for use between JavaScript files.
[src:esbuild/tree-shaking] In modern JavaScript applications, we use module bundlers (e.g., webpack or Rollup) to automatically remove dead code when bundling multiple JavaScript files into single files.
[src:esbuild/tree-shaking] This is important for preparing code that is production ready, for example with clean structures and minimal file size.
